  journal={Jena Economic Research Papers},
  year={2010},
  abstract={This study investigates the role of gender-task stereotypes in explaining gender differences in competitiveness. The authors conducted an experiment with a quantitative task (SUM) and a verbal task (WO), both under different incentive schemes (piece rate, tournament, and revenue sharing). They found that women self-select significantly less into competition against men only in the quantitative task, suggesting that gender-task stereotypes influence women's choices in competitive environments. The study also explored self-selection into incentive schemes with different gender compositions and single-sex groups with different incentive schemes, further supporting their interpretation. The findings highlight the importance of considering task-related factors and gender stereotypes in research on gender differences in competitiveness.},
