  population={Undergraduate students from various disciplines at the Friedrich-Schiller-University, Jena, Germany.},
  intervention={The study involved two tasks: a summation task (SUM) with a strong male connotation and a word-order task (WO) considered gender-neutral. Participants were randomly assigned to different incentive schemes (piece rate, tournament, and revenue sharing) and tasks.},
  findings={The study found that women self-select significantly less into competition against men only in the quantitative task (SUM), suggesting that gender-task stereotypes influence women's choices in competitive environments. This effect was not observed in the verbal task (WO), which is considered gender-neutral.},
  outcomes={The study measured participants' performance in the tasks, their self-selection into different incentive schemes, and their risk attitudes.},
  design={Controlled laboratory experiment with a between-subjects design. Participants were randomly assigned to different incentive schemes and tasks, and their choices and performance were analyzed using regression analysis.},
